BUILD INSTRUCTIONS
1) Install basic build tools:
sudo apt install -y build-essential git make gawk flex bison libgmp-dev libmpfr-dev libmpc-dev python3 binutils perl libisl-dev libzstd-dev tar gzip bzip2

2) Install dependencies:
-SDL2 - Cross platform window creation, input etc.
-SDL2_image - Image file loading
-OpenGL - The original graphics API
-GLEW - Deals with the mess that is OpenGL extensions and versions
-tinyxml - XML parsing
-ENet - Reliable packets on UDP
-Compiler - clang/LLVM default make CXX=g++ for gcc.
-Linker - lld
sudo apt install libenet-dev libsdl2-dev libsdl2-image-dev libglew-dev libtinyxml-dev lld

3) Build/Install 
Linux - Run commands on Makefile in HoverX root directory.
make: Create HoverX. Add -j# to speed things up. # is number of CPUs.
make clean: Remove build files created in the src directory.
make install: Install HoverX in home directory.
make uninstall: Remove HoverX from home directory.

Other - Use CMake to generate build files and then build with them.
cmake -S src -B build: Generate build files in build folder in HoverX root
cmake --build build: Build HoverX in build folder.
mv HoverX ..: Move HoverX to root directory
./HoverX: Execute HoverX.


USER INSTRUCTIONS
Controls:
-Arrow left/right turn
-Arrow up jump
-Left shift gas
-Spacebar brake

Single player:
New room; menu->Sectors->New and pick a map and wait for it to load!

Multiplayer:
the host will need to do a /host 1 to allow connections to him
the connecting players will need to /connect "the host IP address here"

Levels:
alley - old school remake of a hover race track
sumo - demo of a sumo wrestling game mode; not implemented yet
classic 8 - cool map made by Lee!

Commands:
/createroom mapname.xml     //maps should be in levels folder
/leaveroom
/closeroom
/startrace 3(or whatever)   //the laps that will be in the race
/host 1(or 0)               //start a server and allow clients to join
/connect 127.0.0.1          //connect to server
/exit and /quit

Settings:
Window resolution, user name settings stored in settings.xml.

